%N A386820 a(n) is the size of largest subset of {1, 1/2, ..., 1/n} that can be partitioned into two parts with equal sums of elements.
%C A386820 From _David A. Corneth_, Oct 21 2025: (Start)
%C A386820 Some numbers from [1..n] can be excluded as numerators in fractions {1, 1/2, ..., 1/n} as when included the denominators cannot be equal.
%C A386820 For example for n = 16 we cannot have the fraction 1/13 as when included the denominator with it is a multiple of 13. The denominator of the other partition cannot be a multiple of 13 as there is no other multiple of 13 in [1..16] than 13 itself. In a similar fashion we may exclude prime powers >= 16/2 which excludes 9, 11, 13 and 16. Now we are left with [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 10, 12, 14, 15]. Now 16 has been removed we have the prime power 8 that cannot be included either as it is the only multiple of prime power 8 in that list. Repeating this process removes no other numbers so the only possible numbers for n = 16 are [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 10, 12, 14, 15]. These are 11 numbers so a(16) <= 11. (End)
%H A386820 Art of Problem Solving, <a href="https://artofproblemsolving.com/community/c6h2112349p15298955">2020 GQMO Problem 4</a>, which shows that a(n) >= 2*n/5 for sufficiently large n.
%H A386820 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/319">Problem #319</a>, Erdős problems.
%H A386820 Ernest S. Croot III, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/9904181">On Unit Fractions with Denominators in Short Intervals</a>, arXiv:math/9904181 [math.NT], 2001; see <a href="https://eudml.org/doc/279607">also</a>, Acta Arith. (2001), 99-114.
%H A386820 Vincent Jugé, <a href="/A386820/a386820.pdf">Proof that a(n) > c*n for all real numbers c < 1 and sufficiently large n</a>
%F A386820 a(n) = a(n-1) if n/k = p is a prime and p > A001008(k).
%F A386820 a(n) >= (1 - 1/e + o(1))n. (See Erdős Problems link) - _Elijah Beregovsky_, Oct 23 2025
%e A386820 For a(6) = 4, the set {1, 1/2, 1/3, 1/6} is chosen because 1 = 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/6.
%e A386820 The two parts for a(18) = 11 are 1 + 1/5 + 1/6 + 1/15 = 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/4 + 1/9 + 1/10 + 1/12 + 1/18.
%e A386820 The two parts for a(20) = 11 are 1 + 1/9 + 1/10 + 1/15 + 1/18 = 1/2 + 1/3 + 1/5 + 1/6 + 1/12 + 1/20.
%t A386820 SplittableQ[s_]:=Select[Subsets[s,Floor[Length[s]/2]],Total[s]==2Total[#]&,1]=!={};
%t A386820 LargestPrimePowerDivisor[n_]:=Sort[FactorInteger[n],Power@@#1<Power@@#2&][[-1]];
%t A386820 A025529[n_]:=HarmonicNumber[n]*LCM@@Range[n];
%t A386820 FilteredRange[n_]:=If[PrimePowerQ[n],FilteredRange[n-1],Select[Range[n],A025529[Floor[n/Power@@LargestPrimePowerDivisor[#]]]>=LargestPrimePowerDivisor[#][[1]]&]];
%t A386820 a[n_]:=Length[Select[Reverse[Subsets[(1/#)&/@FilteredRange[n]]],SplittableQ[#]&,1][[1]]] (* _Elijah Beregovsky_, Oct 23 2025 *)
